methods.name: templatize
methods.description:
Generates an anonymous `TemplateInstance` class (stored as `this.ctor`)
for the provided template.  This method should be called once per
template to prepare an element for stamping the template, followed
by `stamp` to create new instances of the template.

params.name: mutableData
params.description:
When `true`, the generated class will skip
  strict dirty-checking for objects and arrays (always consider them to
  be "dirty"). Defaults to false.

methods.name: stamp
methods.description:
Creates an instance of the template prepared by `templatize`.  The object
returned is an instance of the anonymous class generated by `templatize`
whose `root` property is a document fragment containing newly cloned
template content, and which has property accessors corresponding to
properties referenced in template bindings.

params.name: model
params.description:
Object containing initial property values to
  populate into the template bindings.

return.desc:
Returns the created instance of
the template prepared by `templatize`.

methods.name: modelForElement
methods.description:
Returns the template "model" (`TemplateInstance`) associated with
a given element, which serves as the binding scope for the template
instance the element is contained in.  A template model should be used
to manipulate data associated with this template instance.

params.name: el
params.description: Element for which to return a template model.

return.desc:
Model representing the binding scope for
  the element.

methods.description:
#### Basic functionality ##### `_(string, t)`
{{ _(‘My translation’, t) }}
#### Interpolation ##### `_(string, [args], t)`
{{ _(‘Hello {0}’, user.name, t) }}

methods.name: ngettext
methods.description:
#### Plurals ##### `ngettext(singular, plural, count, t)`
{{ ngettext(‘My translation’, ‘My translations’, count, t) }}
#### Plurals with interpolation ##### `ngettext(singular, plural, [count and other args], t)`
{{ ngettext(‘My translation for “{1}”’, ‘My {0} translations for “{1}”’, count, ‘hello’, t) }}
_The first number-argument found will be used as ‘count’ to decide plural._

methods.name: pgettext
methods.description:
#### Context ##### `pgettext(context, ‘text’, t)`
{{ pgettext(‘Cancel Invoice’, ‘Cancel’, t) }}
#### Context with interpolation ##### `pgettext(context, ‘text’, [args], t)`
{{ pgettext(‘Cancel Invoice’, ‘Cancel {0}’, document.type, t) }}

methods.name: npgettext
methods.description:
#### Plurals and context ##### `npgettext(context, singular, plural, count, t)`
{{ npgettext('Cancel invoice', ‘My cancellation’, ‘My {0} cancellations’, count, t) }}
#### Plurals and context with interpolation ##### `npgettext(context, singular, plural, count, t)`
{{ npgettext('Cancel invoice', ‘My {1} cancellation’, ‘My {0} {1} cancellations’, count, document.type, t) }}
